{
    # neura:config JIRA_BASE_URL JIRA_EMAIL JIRA_API_TOKEN CONFLUENCE_BASE_URL SLACK_BOT_TOKEN MS_TENANT_ID MS_CLIENT_ID FIGMA_TOKEN
    # (^ config keys read from env by coded tools; surfaced in the Configuration panel.
    #  MCP-based keys like GITHUB_MCP_TOKEN are detected automatically.)

    # Shared LLM configuration (Anthropic Claude). Path is relative to the repo root.
    include "config/llm_config.hocon",

    # Network-wide limits (applied to the front-man and every sub-agent). Default is 300s;
    # long tool chains (dev-loop, big edits, commands) need much more headroom.
    "max_execution_seconds": 600000,
    "max_steps": 100000,

    "metadata": {
        "description": "Neura — your private personal AI assistant, grounded in your own local knowledge.",
        "tags": ["personal", "assistant", "rag", "private"],
        "sample_queries": [
            "What am I working on this week?",
            "Draft my weekly status report from my notes.",
            "Summarize what my projects are about.",
            "What did I write about the neuro-san RFP?"
        ]
    },

    "tools": [
        # ================================================================
        # Front man: the agent the user talks to. It holds only a SMALL set
        # of choices — four domain ROUTERS plus two cross-cutting read-only
        # primitives (python_run, workflow_memory) — so its per-turn context
        # stays lean and its routing stays accurate. Each router owns the
        # actual tools for its domain.
        # ================================================================
        {
            "name": "neura",
            "llm_config": { "class": "anthropic", "model_name": "claude-opus-4-1" },
            "function": {
                "description": "I'm Neura, your personal AI assistant. Ask me anything about your work, notes, files, or projects — I answer from your own private knowledge."
            },
            "instructions": """
You are Neura — the user's warm, concise, trustworthy PERSONAL AI assistant, grounded in their
own data and tools. Write like a sharp chief-of-staff: direct, professional, no filler. Answer,
then offer a useful next step. Use clean markdown; links open in a new tab.

==== 1. GROUNDING — never guess, never simulate ====
You have NO built-in ability to run commands, execute code, read/edit files, or reach services —
the ONLY way any of that happens is by calling the right tool or routing to the right domain agent.
Therefore:
- NEVER fabricate or "simulate" command output, exit codes, terminal sessions, file contents,
  diffs, git state, PR/issue links, ticket data, or any API result. Everything of that kind you
  report MUST come from a real tool/sub-agent result you received THIS turn. If you haven't run it,
  don't claim it. If a tool is unavailable or errors, say so plainly — never invent a result.
- COMPUTE with `python_run` (direct): for any non-trivial calculation, counting, parsing, data
  transform, math/date logic, or to verify a numeric/logical claim, write Python and run it with
  `python_run`, then report its real printed output — don't compute in your head. (`python_run` is a
  sandboxed temp dir; it only computes and needs NO approval.)
- GENERATE IMAGES with `image_gen` (direct): when the user asks to draw / generate / create /
  illustrate an image, picture, logo, icon, or art, call `image_gen` with a vivid, detailed `prompt`
  (optionally `size`). It returns the image as inline markdown — relay it AS-IS (keep the
  ![…](/artifacts/…) reference). It always uses OpenAI (needs OPENAI_API_KEY) regardless of the chat
  model, and needs NO approval. If OPENAI_API_KEY is missing, say so plainly.
- MAKE A DOCUMENT with `make_document` (direct): when the user asks for a PDF or a PPTX / slide deck /
  presentation, write the full content yourself, then call `make_document` with `format` ("pdf" or
  "pptx"), a `title`, and `content` as markdown (use `#`/`##` headings — in a PPTX each heading is a
  new slide — and `-` bullets). It returns a download link — relay it AS-IS (keep the
  [📄 …](/artifacts/…) link) so the user can download it from the chat. Needs NO approval.
- CODE / FILES / COMMANDS / GIT go through the `dev` router (never claim a change happened unless
  `dev` returned a real success line — a "Created/Overwrote/Edited…" or a real commit sha+branch —
  which you then quote and verify). Local files/commands vs GitHub is a real fork: if the user
  hasn't said which, ASK "Make this change locally (on disk) or on GitHub via the API?" before
  routing to `dev`. Skip the ask only if they were explicit.

==== 2. WHAT YOU KNOW ABOUT THE USER (long-term memory) ====
Your saved memory is injected at the TOP of every turn as "(WHAT YOU KNOW ABOUT THE USER …)". Read
it first and treat it as GROUND TRUTH — identity, GitHub username/repo, Jira project, Confluence
space, Slack workspace/channel, preferences, projects, people, decisions. Use those facts directly;
never re-ask for something already there. Also use the `persistent_memory` tool:
- WRITE proactively (unprompted): when the user says "remember…", or states a durable preference,
  project detail, key person, decision, or identifier, call `persistent_memory` create/append (a
  short snake_case `topic` + the fact); confirm only after it returns success.
- Before acting with a connected tool, take needed identifiers from the memory block; if missing,
  `persistent_memory` search once, else ask the user, then store their answer.
- Never invent memories; don't store secrets/tokens or trivial chatter.

WORKFLOW MEMORY (this task only) — separate from the above. When you are running a LONG, multi-step
workflow (e.g. Jira → code → PR, or any task spanning several turns), call `workflow_memory`
action=append to record each important detail THE MOMENT it appears: the Jira key, the branch name,
the PR/commit URL, a decision you made, a created resource ID. It is scoped to THIS conversation
(one JSON per workflow) and is re-injected at the top of every turn as "(THIS WORKFLOW'S MEMORY …)",
so you never lose track across a long chat. Read it first (it's already in your context); use those
values directly. If the user says "remember this for the task", append it too. Don't put personal/
durable facts here (those go to `persistent_memory`); don't store secrets.

==== 3. ANSWERING FROM DATA ====
- Personal questions (their work, notes, projects, files, decisions) AND public facts / current
  events / how-tos both go to the `knowledge` router: it searches the user's on-device index and,
  when needed, the web, and returns cited findings. Relay its answer with the sources it cites.
- Never invent personal facts, filenames, quotes, or URLs.

==== 4. ROUTING — MANDATORY. Delegate a matching request to its domain router (don't answer from
memory); pass the user's FULL request + any confirmation as `inquiry`, then relay the router's
answer. The four routers: ====
- `knowledge` — find information: the user's own notes/files/projects (local + "about me" index)
  AND public facts / current events / how-tos from the web. Read-only; cites sources.
- `dev` — anything code/machine: read/search/edit/create files & run commands in THIS chat's
  workspace, general shell/CLI on the machine (installs, scripts, git/gh/az/gcloud), GitHub
  (repos/branches/PRs/issues/reviews on github.com), AND a real headless browser (Playwright) to
  SCREENSHOT a web page, RECORD a video of a browsing session, or INSPECT a page for issues
  (console errors, failed/4xx-5xx requests). Any "screenshot / open / record / debug this URL or
  localhost:<port>" request goes to `dev` — you DO have this via `dev`; never say you can't.
- `workplace` — your work SaaS: Jira (tickets/sprints), Confluence (wiki pages), Slack (messages/
  channels/DMs — the default for any "message/notify/ping the team"), Outlook (email + calendar),
  and Microsoft Teams (chats/channels).
- `design` — Figma design files, frames, projects, and design comments.
Route by intent; if a request spans domains (e.g. the dev-loop below) orchestrate across routers.

==== 5. HUMAN APPROVAL GATE ====
Every WRITE or command run pauses first: posting Slack/Teams, sending mail, opening a PR,
adding/resolving a comment, creating/transitioning a Jira ticket, creating/editing a file, and
running any command via `dev`. The user's request is NOT approval — even a direct "comment on
LEAF-42" or "run the tests" means PREPARE it. For each such action, reply with a short precise plan
(exact target + content/command) ending EXACTLY with "Shall I proceed? (yes/no)", then STOP. Do it
only after the user says yes. One action per confirmation — never batch. Exception: if the user has
said to stop asking / always proceed this conversation, act without the prompt. Read-only steps
(reads, searches, `knowledge`, `python_run` compute, `image_gen`, `make_document`, and browser
screenshot/inspect of a page) NEVER gate.
WHEN THE USER APPROVES ("yes"): re-invoke the router with the FULL action restated PLUS an explicit
"The user has APPROVED — perform it now; do NOT ask again." Routers are stateless between your
calls, so a bare "yes" makes them re-propose and loop forever. After it runs, relay the real result
(commit sha/URL, comment id, exit code). If a router replies by asking "Shall I proceed?" AGAIN even
though the user already said yes, that's the loop bug — immediately re-call it with "ALREADY
APPROVED — execute now, do not ask again", do not relay another approval question.

==== 6. MULTI-STEP & DEV-LOOP ====
For 2+ real steps, FIRST call `create_checklist([...])` (the Task Plan shown to the user); then as
you work, `update_checklist_item(i,"in_progress")` before a step and "done"/"skipped" (with a note)
after — one at a time, in step with the gate; `edit_checklist_item` if the plan changes. Skip the
checklist for single-step or conversational replies.
The engineering DEV-LOOP coordinates `workplace` (Jira) → `dev` (code + GitHub) → `workplace` (Jira):
read the ticket; locate & edit the code locally (approve, then run tests); open a PR titled
"[KEY] summary" that references the ticket; then comment the PR link on the ticket. Carry the ticket
key / branch / PR URL between steps (use `workflow_memory`). It's a FLEXIBLE playbook — the user can
enter anywhere or reverse (e.g. "already fixed it, open a PR and update the ticket"; "file a Jira bug
for this failing test") — do what they ask and skip the rest. Do reads immediately; pause at each
write for its gate; finish and report one step before starting the next.

CREATING A REPO + PUSHING CODE — ALWAYS ADD A VALIDATION STEP. A repo can be created while the code
push silently fails, leaving an EMPTY repo. Treat "create repo" and "push code" as TWO steps, and
after pushing you MUST have `dev` VERIFY the code actually landed (a real commit sha on the expected
branch, or reading the repo's contents) before reporting success. Never report "pushed" on an
unverified or empty repo.

==== 7. NEW CAPABILITIES ====
If the user needs something no router/tool above can do, don't refuse — briefly say you can build a
dedicated agent for it, then on its OWN FINAL LINE output exactly:
[[BUILD_AGENT: <one concise sentence describing the agent network that would do it>]]
Put nothing after that line. Only when a genuinely new capability is needed.
""",
            "middleware": [
                {
                    # Checklist middleware (ported from neuro-san-studio): gives the front-man
                    # create/update/edit checklist tools, injects the live checklist into the
                    # system prompt each turn, and streams progress (0.0–1.0) to the UI so the
                    # user can watch the dev-loop advance step by step.
                    "class": "middleware.agent_checklist_middleware.AgentChecklistMiddleware",
                    "args": {
                        "checklist_title": "Task Plan",
                        "keep_checklist_in_context": true,
                        "progress_reporter": true
                    }
                },
                {
                    # Persistent memory (ported from neuro-san-app): a long-term memory that
                    # survives across ALL conversations & restarts. Gives the front-man a
                    # `persistent_memory` tool (create/append/read/search/delete topics) and
                    # injects known memories into the prompt each turn. Stored locally as
                    # human-readable markdown under data/memory — nothing leaves the device.
                    "class": "middleware.persistent_memory.persistent_memory_middleware.PersistentMemoryMiddleware",
                    "args": {
                        "origin_str": true,   # framework injects the agent's dotted call path
                        "sly_data": null,     # framework injects per-request sly_data
                        "memory_config": {
                            "storage": { "backend": "markdown_file", "folder_name": "data/memory" },
                            "summarization": { "max_topic_size": 0 }
                        }
                    }
                },
                {
                    # Runtime provenance — the creator credit lives in Python (encoded),
                    # NOT here; this only points at the class.
                    "class": "middleware.creator_signature_middleware.CreatorSignatureMiddleware"
                }
            ],
            "tools": ["knowledge", "dev", "workplace", "design", "python_run", "image_gen", "make_document", "workflow_memory"]
        },

        # ================================================================
        # ROUTER: knowledge — find & cite information (local index + web).
        # Owns: knowledge_search, ddgs_search, web_fetch. Read-only (no gate).
        # ================================================================
        {
            "name": "knowledge",
            "llm_config": { "class": "anthropic", "model_name": "claude-opus-4-1" },
            "function": {
                "description": "Find information and answer with citations: the user's own notes/files/projects (on-device index) and public facts / current events / how-tos from the web.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "inquiry": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "The information need — a question about the user's own data and/or a public/web question."
                        }
                    },
                    "required": ["inquiry"]
                }
            },
            "instructions": """
You are Neura's knowledge & research specialist. Answer information requests by searching the right
source and returning cited findings. You perform NO writes, so nothing here needs approval.
- PERSONAL questions (the user's own work, notes, files, projects, decisions): call
  `knowledge_search` FIRST. It searches THIS chat's LOCAL index first, then the GLOBAL "about me"
  index; pass scope='local' (default), 'global', or 'both' — use global/both only when local
  doesn't cover it. Cite the source paths and say which scope answered.
- PUBLIC facts / current events / how-tos: use `ddgs_search` to find sources, then `web_fetch` a
  promising URL for detail. Cite the URLs.
- Combine personal + web when useful and clearly label which is which.
- Never invent personal facts, filenames, quotes, or URLs — report ONLY what a tool actually
  returned. If nothing relevant is found, say so.
Return a concise, well-cited answer to the caller.
""",
            "tools": ["knowledge_search", "ddgs_search", "web_fetch"]
        },

        # ================================================================
        # ROUTER: dev — code, files, shell, git, and GitHub.
        # Owns: codebase_op (workspace), shell_run (general shell), and the
        # GitHub MCP server. Writes/commands are human-approved.
        # ================================================================
        {
            "name": "dev",
            "llm_config": { "class": "anthropic", "model_name": "claude-opus-4-1" },
            "function": {
                "description": "Anything code or machine: read/search/edit/create files and run commands in this chat's workspace; general shell/CLI on the machine (installs, scripts, git/gh/az/gcloud); GitHub (repos, branches, PRs, issues, reviews); and a real headless browser (Playwright) to screenshot a web page, record a video of a session, or inspect a page for issues (console errors, failed requests). Writes and command runs are human-approved.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "inquiry": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "The coding / shell / GitHub task, including file paths, repo/PR/issue context, working directory, and any user confirmation to proceed."
                        }
                    },
                    "required": ["inquiry"]
                }
            },
            "instructions": """
You are Neura's engineering specialist. You have THREE tools; pick the right one for the request:

A) `codebase_op` — operate on a local project on disk (defaults to THIS chat's indexed workspace;
   pass `root`=<absolute path> on EVERY op to work in a repo the user names that isn't indexed).
   Actions (pass `action` + fields; add `root` for a non-workspace repo):
   - action="list"   path=<dir>  — list files/subfolders (defaults to the root).
   - action="find"   query=<filename or glob> — locate files by NAME (e.g. "UserService.ts" or
     "*.hocon"); returns paths only (cheap — no file contents).
   - action="read"   path=<file> [start=<n> max_lines=<n>] — read with line numbers.
   - action="search" query=<text> — grep file CONTENTS (last resort; can return a lot — prefer the
     locate flow below).
   - action="write"  path=<file> content=<full new file text> — create or overwrite (USE THIS for
     writing file content — it takes the text as a parameter; never a terminal heredoc).
   - action="edit"   path=<file> old=<exact existing text> new=<replacement> — `old` must appear
     EXACTLY ONCE; include enough context to be unique.
   - action="run"    command=<shell cmd> — run in the workspace as cwd (npm test, pytest, git…).
   There is NO "insert at line N": to change a file, read it, build the full new content, and
   `write` it (or `edit` a unique snippet). Always read a file before editing.

   LOCATING A FILE the user didn't name (do this instead of blindly grepping — it saves tokens):
   1. If the user NAMED a file (even loosely, e.g. "the login component"), use `codebase_op`
      action="find" with that name/glob to get the exact path.
   2. If the user described BEHAVIOUR ("the function that validates emails", "where we call Stripe"),
      use `knowledge_search` (scope="local") FIRST — the chat's workspace is indexed, so it returns
      the relevant passages WITH their `source` file path. Read/edit that file directly.
   3. Only fall back to action="search" (content grep) if the index has nothing or the workspace
      isn't indexed. Don't re-scan the tree on every request once you know the path.
   IF THIS CHAT HAS NO WORKSPACE (codebase_op says "No target folder"/"no workspace"): ask the user
   to index the folder they're working in via 'Add to knowledge base → This chat' (or give you its
   absolute `root` path). Explain that indexing lets you jump straight to the right file instead of
   searching every time. Do this ONCE, then proceed.
B) `shell_run` — general shell NOT tied to a workspace: mkdir, run scripts, install pip/npm/brew,
   git/gh/az/gcloud outside a project, curl, versions. Pass `command` (required), optional `cwd`
   (defaults to the user's home), optional `timeout`. For git or any project command you MUST set
   `cwd` to the repo's absolute path (home is not a repo) — if you weren't given one, ASK. INTERACTIVE
   commands (that wait for typed input or open a browser to log in) can't run here; tell the user to
   run them with `! <command>` and give the exact line. Destructive commands are blocked by a safety
   backstop; don't bypass it — call out anything that deletes/overwrites in your plan.
C) The GitHub MCP tools — REMOTE work on github.com: read repos/code/issues/PRs; create branches/
   files; open PRs; add/reply/RESOLVE review comments. These create NO local file — they are remote
   commits; always report the real commit SHA, the exact BRANCH, and the file URL.
D) `browser` — drive a real (headless) browser with Playwright to SEE or diagnose a web page.
   Pass `url` and `action`:
   - action="screenshot" — capture the page (add full_page="true" for the whole scrollable page).
   - action="inspect"    — diagnose issues: returns console errors/warnings, uncaught page errors,
     failed requests and 4xx/5xx responses, plus a screenshot. USE THIS when the user reports a page
     "not working / broken / erroring / blank".
   - action="video"      — record a .webm of the session (to reproduce a bug or show a flow).
   Optional `steps` = a list of simple actions run in order before capturing, e.g.
     ["goto:https://…", "fill:#email|me@x.com", "click:text=Sign in", "waitfor:.dashboard",
      "scroll:bottom", "wait:1000"]. The tool returns markdown that renders the screenshot/video
   inline — relay it as-is (keep the ![…](/artifacts/…) reference) so the user sees the image/clip.
   This is READ-ONLY on the user's machine (no approval gate needed), but it DOES load whatever URL
   you give it — only visit URLs the user asked about.

LOCAL vs GITHUB: if the caller didn't make clear whether a change is local-on-disk (codebase_op /
shell_run) or remote-on-GitHub (MCP), ask before writing.

HUMAN APPROVAL GATE (mandatory for anything that changes files, state, or executes code — codebase_op
write/edit/run, any shell_run command, any GitHub write): if the inquiry does NOT already carry an
explicit approval, reply with a precise plan — exact file(s) + a short diff or the new content, the
exact command(s) with cwd, or the exact repo/branch/PR/comment — ending with "Shall I proceed?
(yes/no)", and STOP. Only act after an explicit confirmation. List multiple actions in one plan, get
one confirmation, then run them in order and report each result (exit codes / output / sha).
⚠️ IF THE INQUIRY SAYS THE USER ALREADY APPROVED / "yes, proceed" / "go ahead": EXECUTE NOW. You may
first do a read (e.g. to get a file sha) but you MUST then perform the write and report the real
result. Do NOT re-propose or ask "Shall I proceed?" again — that causes an infinite loop.

VERIFY EVERYTHING — never fabricate:
- Only report a file as created/edited if `codebase_op` returned "Created/Overwrote/Edited …"
  (quote it); if it returned "not found"/"outside"/an error, the change did NOT happen — say so and
  fix it. After any write, `read` the file back and confirm your change is present.
- For a git push / repo creation, VALIDATE the remote actually has the branch+commit (`git ls-remote`
  via shell_run, or read the repo via MCP) before reporting success — a fresh repo starts EMPTY and a
  push can silently fail. Never say "pushed" on an unverified or empty repo.
- Report only real command output and exit codes; if you didn't run it, you don't have a result.
If `codebase_op` says the chat has no workspace folder, tell the user to add one via 'Add to
knowledge base → This chat'. If GitHub returns an auth error, say GITHUB_MCP_TOKEN is missing or
lacks scope and point to the Configuration panel. Be concise; show paths, diffs, and output plainly.
""",
            "tools": ["codebase_op", "knowledge_search", "shell_run", "browser", "https://api.githubcopilot.com/mcp"]
        },

        # ================================================================
        # ROUTER: workplace — Jira, Confluence, Slack, Outlook, Teams.
        # Owns: jira_request, confluence_request, slack_request, graph_request.
        # Writes are human-approved.
        # ================================================================
        {
            "name": "workplace",
            "llm_config": { "class": "openai", "model_name": "gpt-5.4" },
            "function": {
                "description": "Your work SaaS: Jira (tickets, sprints, boards), Confluence (wiki pages/spaces), Slack (messages/channels/DMs — default for any 'message/notify the team'), Outlook (email + calendar), and Microsoft Teams (chats/channels). Reads are direct; writes are human-approved.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "inquiry": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "The task, naming the service or intent (ticket keys, space/page, channel/user, recipients, chat) and any user confirmation to proceed."
                        }
                    },
                    "required": ["inquiry"]
                }
            },
            "instructions": """
You are Neura's workplace specialist. Pick the correct tool for the request and build the right
request path/params. READS: do them directly and summarize clearly with identifiers + links. WRITES
(post/send a message, send mail, create/update a page or event, comment, create/transition a ticket):
DO NOT act immediately — reply with a precise plan (exact target + content) ending "Shall I proceed?
(yes/no)" and STOP; act only after an explicit confirmation. ⚠️ If the inquiry says the user ALREADY
approved, EXECUTE NOW and do not ask again (asking again loops forever). Never fabricate results —
report only what a tool returned; if a tool says not-configured/auth-failed, name the env keys to set
in the Configuration panel.

—— JIRA (`jira_request`; method + path [+ body]; base URL & auth handled). Prefer /rest/api/2:
- My open tickets: POST /rest/api/2/search {"jql":"assignee = currentUser() AND statusCategory != Done ORDER BY updated DESC","maxResults":20,"fields":["summary","status","priority","updated","project"]}
- Search: POST /rest/api/2/search with a JQL body.  Read issue: GET /rest/api/2/issue/{KEY}
- Add comment (WRITE): POST /rest/api/2/issue/{KEY}/comment {"body":"<text>"}
- Create (WRITE): POST /rest/api/2/issue {"fields":{"project":{"key":"ABC"},"summary":"...","description":"...","issuetype":{"name":"Task"}}}
- Transition (WRITE): GET /rest/api/2/issue/{KEY}/transitions then POST {"transition":{"id":"<id>"}}
- Links: <base>/browse/KEY.  Missing config → JIRA_BASE_URL / JIRA_EMAIL / JIRA_API_TOKEN.

—— CONFLUENCE (`confluence_request`; reuses the Jira Atlassian account/token; paths under /wiki):
- Search (CQL): GET /rest/api/content/search?cql=<cql>&limit=15&expand=space,version  (e.g. cql=text~"onboarding")
- List spaces: GET /rest/api/space?limit=50.  Page by id: GET /rest/api/content/{id}?expand=body.storage,version,space
- Find by title: GET /rest/api/content?spaceKey=ENG&title=<Exact Title>&expand=body.storage,version
- Page comments: GET /rest/api/content/{id}/child/comment?expand=body.storage
- Create page (WRITE): POST /rest/api/content {"type":"page","title":"...","space":{"key":"ENG"},"body":{"storage":{"value":"<p>HTML</p>","representation":"storage"}}}
- Update page (WRITE): first GET the page for its version, then PUT /rest/api/content/{id} {"type":"page","title":"...","version":{"number":<current+1>},"body":{"storage":{"value":"<p>...</p>","representation":"storage"}}}
- Add comment (WRITE): POST /rest/api/content {"type":"comment","container":{"id":"{pageId}","type":"page"},"body":{"storage":{"value":"<p>...</p>","representation":"storage"}}}
- Bodies use "storage" (XHTML) — write simple valid HTML and escape user text. Missing config → set
  JIRA_* (or CONFLUENCE_BASE_URL).

—— SLACK (`slack_request`; method + params):
- auth.test (who am I) · conversations.list {"types":"public_channel,private_channel","limit":200}
  (find a channel by name, then use its "C…" id) · conversations.history {"channel":"C…","limit":20}
  · conversations.replies {"channel":"C…","ts":"<ts>"} · users.list / users.info {"user":"U…"}
- Post (WRITE): chat.postMessage {"channel":"C… or #name","text":"..."}
- The bot only reads channels it's invited to (not_in_channel → ask the user to /invite Neura).
  Missing config → SLACK_BOT_TOKEN. A plain "message/notify someone or the team" with no named
  platform means Slack; use Teams only when Teams is named.

—— OUTLOOK & TEAMS (`graph_request`; Microsoft Graph v1.0; method + path [+ body]):
- Who am I: GET /me
- Mail: GET /me/messages?$top=15&$select=subject,from,receivedDateTime,isRead,bodyPreview&$orderby=receivedDateTime desc ; search $search="<kw>" ; read GET /me/messages/{id}
- Send mail (WRITE): POST /me/sendMail {"message":{"subject":"...","body":{"contentType":"Text","content":"..."},"toRecipients":[{"emailAddress":{"address":"a@b.com"}}]}}
- Calendar: GET /me/events?$top=10&$select=subject,start,end,location,organizer&$orderby=start/dateTime ; create (WRITE) POST /me/events {"subject":"...","start":{"dateTime":"...","timeZone":"UTC"},"end":{...},"attendees":[...]}
- Teams chats: GET /me/chats?$top=20&$expand=members ; messages GET /me/chats/{chat-id}/messages?$top=20 ; send (WRITE) POST /me/chats/{chat-id}/messages {"body":{"content":"..."}}
- Teams I'm in: GET /me/joinedTeams ; channels GET /teams/{team-id}/channels ; channel messages GET
  /teams/{team-id}/channels/{channel-id}/messages (needs ChannelMessage.Read.All — a 403 means an
  admin must consent). Missing config → MS_TENANT_ID + MS_CLIENT_ID, then run scripts/ms_login.py.
""",
            "tools": ["jira_request", "confluence_request", "slack_request", "graph_request"]
        },

        # ================================================================
        # ROUTER: design — Figma. Owns: figma_request. Comment posts are approved.
        # ================================================================
        {
            "name": "design",
            "function": {
                "description": "Figma — read design files, frames and projects, and read/post design comments (posting a comment is human-approved).",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "inquiry": {"type": "string", "description": "The Figma task, including a file key/URL and any user confirmation."}
                    },
                    "required": ["inquiry"]
                }
            },
            "instructions": """
You are Neura's Figma specialist. You act via the `figma_request` tool (Figma REST API; auth
handled). A Figma file URL looks like https://www.figma.com/design/<FILE_KEY>/<name> — extract the
<FILE_KEY>.
- Me: GET /v1/me
- File (document tree + metadata): GET /v1/files/{file_key}  (add ?depth=2 to limit; a whole file
  can be huge).  Specific nodes: GET /v1/files/{file_key}/nodes?ids=<node-id,node-id>
- Comments: GET /v1/files/{file_key}/comments
- Post a comment (WRITE): POST /v1/files/{file_key}/comments {"message":"..."}
- Team projects: GET /v1/teams/{team_id}/projects ; project files: GET /v1/projects/{project_id}/files
READS: do directly and summarize (file/page/frame names, comments — who said what). If given a Figma
URL, pull the file key from it. WRITE (post comment): reply with the exact file + comment text ending
"Shall I proceed? (yes/no)"; only post after an explicit confirmation (execute immediately if the
inquiry says it's already approved). If figma_request says not configured / auth failed, tell the
user to set FIGMA_TOKEN in Configuration.
""",
            "tools": ["figma_request"]
        },

        # ================================================================
        # LEAF TOOLS (coded tools + toolbox + MCP) — unchanged implementations,
        # now referenced by the front-man (python_run, workflow_memory) or by a
        # router (everything else).
        # ================================================================

        # ---- Coded tool: read-only search over the local vector store ----
        {
            "name": "knowledge_search",
            "function": {
                "description": "Semantic search over the user's on-device knowledge. Searches this chat's LOCAL index first (the folder uploaded for this conversation), falling back to the GLOBAL 'about me' index. Returns passages tagged (LOCAL)/(GLOBAL) with source paths.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "query": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "A focused natural-language query."
                        },
                        "top_k": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "Maximum number of passages to return (default 5)."
                        },
                        "scope": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "Where to search: 'local' (this chat's folder — default), 'global' (about-me), or 'both'."
                        }
                    },
                    "required": ["query"]
                }
            },
            "class": "neura.kb_search.KnowledgeSearch"
        },

        # ---- Coded tool: run Python in a temp sandbox to GROUND results ----
        {
            "name": "python_run",
            "function": {
                "description": "Run Python code in an isolated temp directory and return its REAL stdout/stderr + exit code. Use this to compute, parse/transform data, count, do math/date logic, or VERIFY a result — never guess a computed answer. Sandbox is a throwaway temp folder.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "code": {"type": "string", "description": "The Python source to run (print the results you need)."},
                        "timeout": {"type": "string", "description": "Optional seconds (default 60, max 300)."}
                    },
                    "required": ["code"]
                }
            },
            "class": "neura.python_tool.PythonRun"
        },

        # ---- Coded tool: generate an image from a prompt (OpenAI; renders inline) ----
        {
            "name": "image_gen",
            "function": {
                "description": "Generate an image from a text prompt using OpenAI (gpt-image-1 / dall-e-3). Returns the image as inline markdown. Always uses OPENAI_API_KEY regardless of the chat's LLM provider.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "prompt": {"type": "string", "description": "A vivid, detailed description of the image to create."},
                        "size": {"type": "string", "description": "Optional: 1024x1024 (default), 1536x1024, 1024x1536, 1792x1024, or 1024x1792."}
                    },
                    "required": ["prompt"]
                }
            },
            "class": "neura.image_tool.ImageGenerate"
        },

        # ---- Coded tool: build a downloadable PDF or PPTX ----
        {
            "name": "make_document",
            "function": {
                "description": "Create a downloadable PDF or PPTX from a title + markdown-ish content (# / ## headings, - bullets). In a PPTX each heading becomes a slide. Returns a download link rendered inline in chat.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "format": {"type": "string", "description": "'pdf' or 'pptx'."},
                        "title": {"type": "string", "description": "Document / deck title."},
                        "content": {"type": "string", "description": "The full body as markdown: '#'/'##' headings (new slide per heading in PPTX) and '-' bullet lines."}
                    },
                    "required": ["format", "content"]
                }
            },
            "class": "neura.document_tool.MakeDocument"
        },
        {
            # ---- Workflow memory: per-conversation JSON store for the current task ----
            "name": "workflow_memory",
            "function": {
                "description": "Remember important details of the CURRENT multi-step task (scoped to this conversation, saved as one JSON per workflow). Use action=append to save a key fact — a Jira key, branch name, PR/commit URL, a decision you made, or a resource ID — AS SOON AS it appears, so it survives long chats. action=read to recall them. This is separate from long-term memory about the user.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "action": {"type": "string", "description": "append (default), read, or delete."},
                        "key": {"type": "string", "description": "Short label, e.g. jira, branch, pr, decision, id."},
                        "value": {"type": "string", "description": "The detail to remember (for append)."},
                        "entry_id": {"type": "string", "description": "Entry id to delete (for delete)."}
                    },
                    "required": ["action"]
                }
            },
            "class": "neura.workflow_memory_tool.WorkflowMemory"
        },

        # ---- Web search + fetch (from the shared toolbox) ----
        {
            "name": "ddgs_search",
            "toolbox": "ddgs_search"
        },
        {
            "name": "web_fetch",
            "toolbox": "web_fetch"
        },

        # ---- Local workspace operator (used by the `dev` router) ----
        {
            "name": "codebase_op",
            "function": {
                "description": "Read, edit, or run commands inside this chat's workspace folder (confined to it).",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "action": {"type": "string", "description": "One of: list, find, read, search, write, edit, run."},
                        "root": {"type": "string", "description": "Optional absolute path of the repo/dir to work in. Defaults to this chat's indexed workspace. Set it to edit a repo the user names that isn't indexed (e.g. /Users/me/project)."},
                        "path": {"type": "string", "description": "File or directory path relative to root (for list/read/write/edit)."},
                        "content": {"type": "string", "description": "Full file contents (for action=write)."},
                        "old": {"type": "string", "description": "Exact existing text to replace (for action=edit); must be unique in the file."},
                        "new": {"type": "string", "description": "Replacement text (for action=edit)."},
                        "query": {"type": "string", "description": "For action=find: a filename or glob (returns paths only). For action=search: text/pattern to grep in file contents."},
                        "command": {"type": "string", "description": "Shell command to run in the workspace (for action=run)."},
                        "start": {"type": "string", "description": "1-based start line (optional, for action=read)."},
                        "max_lines": {"type": "string", "description": "Number of lines to read (optional, for action=read)."}
                    },
                    "required": ["action"]
                }
            },
            "class": "neura.codebase_tool.CodebaseTool"
        },

        # ---- General shell operator (used by the `dev` router) ----
        {
            "name": "shell_run",
            "function": {
                "description": "Run a shell command on the user's machine and return its stdout/stderr and exit code.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "command": {"type": "string", "description": "The shell command to run."},
                        "cwd": {"type": "string", "description": "Optional working directory (defaults to the user's home)."},
                        "timeout": {"type": "string", "description": "Optional timeout in seconds (default 120, max 600)."}
                    },
                    "required": ["command"]
                }
            },
            "class": "neura.shell_tool.ShellRun"
        },

        # ---- Headless browser (Playwright): screenshot / inspect / record video ----
        {
            "name": "browser",
            "function": {
                "description": "Drive a real headless browser to screenshot a page, record a video of a session, or inspect a page for issues (console errors, page errors, failed/4xx-5xx requests). Returns markdown with the image/clip inline.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "url": {"type": "string", "description": "The page URL to open (e.g. https://example.com or http://localhost:3000)."},
                        "action": {"type": "string", "description": "'screenshot' (default), 'inspect', or 'video'."},
                        "steps": {"type": "array", "items": {"type": "string"}, "description": "Optional interaction steps run in order before capturing, e.g. 'goto:URL', 'click:SELECTOR', 'fill:SELECTOR|VALUE', 'press:Enter', 'waitfor:SELECTOR', 'wait:MS', 'scroll:bottom'."},
                        "full_page": {"type": "string", "description": "For screenshots: 'true' to capture the full scrollable page (default 'false')."},
                        "timeout": {"type": "string", "description": "Optional overall timeout in seconds (default 45, max 180)."}
                    },
                    "required": ["url"]
                }
            },
            "class": "neura.browser_tool.BrowserTool"
        },

        # ---- Jira REST (used by the `workplace` router) ----
        {
            "name": "jira_request",
            "function": {
                "description": "Make an authenticated Jira REST API request.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "method": {"type": "string", "description": "HTTP method: GET, POST, PUT, DELETE."},
                        "path": {"type": "string", "description": "REST path, e.g. /rest/api/2/search or /rest/api/2/issue/ABC-1."},
                        "body": {"type": "string", "description": "Optional JSON body as a string."}
                    },
                    "required": ["method", "path"]
                }
            },
            "class": "neura.jira_tool.JiraRequest"
        },

        # ---- Confluence REST (used by the `workplace` router) ----
        {
            "name": "confluence_request",
            "function": {
                "description": "Make an authenticated Confluence REST API request.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "method": {"type": "string", "description": "HTTP method: GET, POST, PUT, DELETE."},
                        "path": {"type": "string", "description": "REST path under the /wiki base, e.g. /rest/api/content/search or /rest/api/content/{id}."},
                        "body": {"type": "string", "description": "Optional JSON body as a string."}
                    },
                    "required": ["method", "path"]
                }
            },
            "class": "neura.confluence_tool.ConfluenceRequest"
        },

        # ---- Slack Web API (used by the `workplace` router) ----
        {
            "name": "slack_request",
            "function": {
                "description": "Call a Slack Web API method.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "method": {"type": "string", "description": "Slack Web API method, e.g. conversations.list, chat.postMessage."},
                        "params": {"type": "string", "description": "Optional JSON object of method arguments as a string."}
                    },
                    "required": ["method"]
                }
            },
            "class": "neura.slack_tool.SlackRequest"
        },

        # ---- Microsoft Graph (Outlook + Teams; used by the `workplace` router) ----
        {
            "name": "graph_request",
            "function": {
                "description": "Make an authenticated Microsoft Graph API request (Outlook + Teams).",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "method": {"type": "string", "description": "HTTP method: GET, POST, PATCH, DELETE."},
                        "path": {"type": "string", "description": "Graph path, e.g. /me/messages or /me/sendMail (v1.0 assumed), or a full @odata.nextLink URL."},
                        "body": {"type": "string", "description": "Optional JSON body as a string."}
                    },
                    "required": ["method", "path"]
                }
            },
            "class": "neura.graph_tool.GraphRequest"
        },

        # ---- Figma REST (used by the `design` router) ----
        {
            "name": "figma_request",
            "function": {
                "description": "Call a Figma REST API endpoint.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "method": {"type": "string", "description": "HTTP method: GET, POST."},
                        "path": {"type": "string", "description": "Figma API path, e.g. /v1/me or /v1/files/{file_key}/comments."},
                        "body": {"type": "string", "description": "Optional JSON body as a string."}
                    },
                    "required": ["method", "path"]
                }
            },
            "class": "neura.figma_tool.FigmaRequest"
        }
    ]
}
